{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/0041421101A/1945091401/0336.xml":{"full_text":"V\no>o.\nV\nTHE PEOPLE'S VOICE\nC\u00dcWAW\nI\n\n35\nr\u00fcS/\u00e0'\nft\nft\nws\nft\n\nm\ngf\nHELENA, MONTANA, SEPTEMBER 14, 1945\nPrice Five Cents\nVol. VI\u2014No. 42\nWhat's Gers\u00bb? On?\nfliat\nThe sudden end of the war find* 07 3}%?* ^b^ r the same\ncondition, generally speaking as the rest of th\u00e9 A is far\nas planning for the post-war period is concerned,\nnothing has been done to meet the problems of providing op\nportunities for returning war workers and service men and\nwomen to re-establish themselves here where they formerly\nlived.\n\u00b0n\nPractically\nAs I have said, the same is largely true of conditions in\nother states. But, if we are to judge by recent press reports\nof expressions by so-called leaders, nothing will be done in the\nfuture in Montana. These misnamed \"leaders\" apparently\nwant to lull us into a state of complacency; into believing that\neverything is rosy here and there is no call for action.\nIn a recent speech, Senator Wheeler is reported to have\ncalled attention to the \"fortunate\" circumstance that Montana\nis not an industrialized state; that it has no problems of re\nand inferred, clearly enough that there is ample\nthe farms of the state for all returning citizens. While\nconversion\nroom on\nhe probably did not so state, certainly the implications of this\nspeech were of the same stripe as the speeches of other Mon\ntana Power Company and ACM Company protagonists, that\nMontana should remain as merely a source of raw material\nproduction for the benefit of eastern monopoly.\nAn Associated Press dispatch, date-lined \"Helena, Sept. 8\"\nheadlined by the corporation press \"State Leader Hits Federal\nJobless Plan\" tells about the appearance of Barclay Craighead,\nchairman of the Unemployment Compensation Commission of\nMontana, before the senate finance committee in opposition to\nthe proposal to increase by federal contributions to the states,\nthe payments to the jobless during their unemployment. We\nreprint a part of this story below;\n\"In Montana, our position before the committee op\nposed the paying of unemployment benefits through bond\nissues or without proper taxation,\" Craighead explained.\n\"The $25 weekly benefit for 26 weeks as proposed by the\nadministration we feel is entirely out of line, and that at\nthe moment or even within the next six months there will\nbe no emergency in Montana calling for such payments.'\nThe chairman said that about eight state administra\ntors of unemployment compensation agencies and two gov\nappeared before the committees in opposition to\nernors\nthe bill.\nCraighead testified that the \"full employment\" bill\nwould permanently injure the social security program as\na whole.\nCraighead stated that Montana is opposed to the leg\nislation because:\n\"Sound legislation should always have earmarked tax\nfunds provided.\n\"It throws tax burden from employers or beneficiaries\nto the general public.\n\"It fails to extend benefits to those yet\nthe unemployment laws.\n\"It tends toward uniformity of benefits in a country\nwhere the people are not uniform.\n\"The end of the war will cause the rise of many social\nand economic conflicts held under by the war emergency.\n\"It would threaten the solvency of the unemployment\ncompensation funds.\n\"This legislation, and all similar legislation, deceives\nthe people by hiding the costs.\"\nUndoubtedly, the corporation press felt justified in desig\nnating Craighead a \"state leader\" because he was named in a\nstory written in a sarcastic vein in the leading republican week\nly paper in the state as one of the \"high command of the Non\npartisan Committee for Political Action\" along with Senator\nBurt Wheeler, Governor Ford and Burke Clements.\nThere need not be much doubt about how the unemployed\nwill feel about Craighead's reported statement that \"The $25\nweekly benefit for 26 weeks as proposed by the administration\nis entirely out of line\". \"Out of line\" with what? Would it\nbe out of line for an unemployed man with a family to draw\nthat much when prices for necessities are what they are?\nPerhaps Mr. Craighead will explain why, according to the\nreport, he claims that the full employment bill would perma\nnently injure the social security program as a whole. Doesn't\nhe want everyone to have a job? Is he afraid that if everyone\nis assured of employment there will be no need for an unem\nployment compensation organization and he would lose his\nsoft job?\nPassing over his reported arrogant assumption of authority\nto speak for Montana, we note that he objects to the proposal\nto augment state unemployment funds with federal funds be\ncause \"It throws tax burden from employers or beneficiaries to\nthe general public\",\nit would be a crime of greater degree only than is presently the\nIf Craighead is so acutely concerned about expenditure\nof public funds, how come his conscience permits him to accept\na check on federal funds for his services as chairman of the\nUnemployment Compensation Commission each month?\nHe objects to the proposal to increase unemployment com\npensation to the ones now covered because all classes of citizens\nare not covered. He might just as well have said: \"Let\nthose now covered half starve because others are completely\nMaybe he has something there, but if so,\ncase.\nstarving.\"\nHe is against \"uniformity of benefits in a country where\nHe must have some confidential\n\nthe people are not uniform\",\ninformation that people in some sections of the country do not\nget as hungry as they do in other sections.\nJust how Craighead figures augmentation of unemploy\nment compensation payments with federal funds would jeop\nardize the solvency of state unemployment compensation funds\nmust be something hidden from ordinary understanding and\npossible of comprehension by master-minds like his, only,\nfeel properly humble.\nNow another thing: Eight months have elapsed since the\nlegislature provided a brain trust to solve all of Montana's post\nwar unemployment problems by apportionment for construc\ntion here and there of the monticulous sum of five milli\u00e9ns of\nFrom press reports, we learn that this brain trust has\nrun into difficulties, finding need for more funds to meet even\nrequired expenditures. So apparently it hasn't done anything\nand even the profit-hungry contractors haven't been able to\n\u00df\nWe\ndollars.\nspur it to action.\nSo, again, maybe it's time for the people to take a hand.\nCertainly it's time to question the integrity and motives of the\n\"leaders\" who want us to just drift along.\nCO-OPERATIVE\nHOSPITALS IN\nNORTHWEST\nThree More Co-operative\nHospitals Being Organized\nIn Pacific Northwest; Dr.\nShadid to Move to Seattle\nTo Aid New Hospitals.\nWALLA WALLA, Wash. (CLNS)\u2014\nThe whirlwind tour of the Pacific\nnorthwest which Dr. Michael Shadid\nmade in August is already bearing\nfruit. A Co-operative Hospital Asso\nciation has been organized at Sand\nPoint, Idaho and application is being\nmade for a charter. A second organi\nzation is under way at Buhl, Idaho\nand plans are being made for a co-op\nhospital at Salem, Oregon with very\nstrong interest in Bremerton, Wash\nington; Seattle, and Rupert, Idaho.\nDuring Dr. Shadid's tour, he trav\neled 2,000 miles by auto from Salem,\nOregon through Washington and Idaho\nand met with raoer than 2,000 co-op\nerative leaders according to R. M.\nMitchell, educational director of Pa\ncific Supply Co-operative, who trav\neled with him.\nPreliminary plans for hospital asso\nciations were already under discus\nsion at several points. More than a\nthousand people gathered at the an\nnual co-operative picnic at Sand Point,\nIdaho to hear Dr. Shadid discuss the\nvery practical plan of organization\nand a few days later the Co-op wired\nto the Pacific Supply Co-operative in\nWalla Walla saying the organization\nhad been completed and application\nwas being made for a charter for the\nhospital.\nAt Buhl. Idaho, a representative of\nthe local co-operative, the Grange, and\nthe Chamber of Commerce have been\ntalking about building a community\nhospital for more than a year. Two\nhundred people took time away from\ncelebrating the end of the war, August\n14 to listen to Dr. Shadid. Twenty\nfive immediately signed up for $100\nlife-time membership in a community\nco-op hospital.\nAt Salem. Oregon, the Farmers Un\nion has been woVking for several years\non a proposal for a co-op hospital.\nThe meeting with Dr. Shadid pushed\nthings forward rapidly.\nIn Seattle, labor, church and co-op\nerative leaders filled the hall to hear\nDr. Shadid and remained to discuss\npre-paid medical care into the \"small\nhours of the morning\". The goal in\n(Continued on Page Four)\nCO-OP LABOR\nCONFERENCE\nHELD IN WISC.\nRACINE Wise. (CLNS) How to\npack buying power into union-won dol\nlars was the leading topic of the\nthird Co-ops and Labor Conference\non organization held at Union hall\nhere September 8 and 9.\nExpected to draw delegates from\nco-ops and unions in several states,\nthe conference, through speakers,\ntours, films and discussions consid\nered how consumer co-ops can prevent\nlabor's wage gains from being wiped\nout by price boosting.\nOutstanding speakers were J. F.\nFriedrich, Wisconsin regional AFL di\nrector; Nelson Cruikshank, AFL social\nsecurity director, Washington; Don\nald Schwartz, university of Wisconsin,\neconomics department; Ernest Callo\nway, educational director, United\nTransport Service Employees CIO;\nHarvey Kitzman, president, Local 180\nUnited Auto Workers CIO; and Jack\nSchmidt, president, Building Laborers\nDistrict Council, Racine.\nPanel discussions on Sunday, Sep\ntember 9 were devoted to housing,\nhealth care, credit unions and insur\nance, as well as food distribution,\ndairy service, petroleum and electrical\ngoods distribution. Co-operative ex\nperts on these topics were present to\naid in the discussions.\nby Yemen\nCONGRESSMAN DRIPP\noses 4 ra\n1\nA\n\nrr\nS'\nk\n\n\nATI\n\n\nl\u00e0\n\n\u2022t)\nII\nMil\n7?\n\ny\n\n\u25a0S' y\nyr\n\nj\n\n\n\\mz\ni/W\nFP\n\"he just loves to watch unemployment lives.*\nONE FIGHT THAT STILL GOES ON!\n\u25a0y\nVi;.\nrSv.\n\u25a0\u00absc\nI\nv>.v,. y\nV;\n\n\n\u25a0\u00ce-\n\nSi\nft\n\\&t\n<1\n4\nk ECo\nN0r\u00e7, c\nStabilization\nDA*\ny.v\nJ\n\nyM\n's ft\n\nA\nr\nVi\n\n\n\nVf\n\nmm\nym,\nm\n\n\u25a0i:\nM-301\nf i\u00ab gy!)\n0*1\n4\nMVA INTERESTS\nFURTHERED IN\nSTATES'MEETINGS\nThe recent Nebraska statewide con\nference on MVA featured talks by\nGlenn J. Talbott, chairman of the Na\ntional Farmers Union Natural Re\nsources Development Committee, Ray\nmond R. Tucker, vice chairman of the\nRegional Committee for MVA, and\nHarry Trustim, Omaha city commis\nsioner. C. Petrus Peterson, speaker\nof the state legislature, presided. The\nconference was sponsored by the\nOmaha Progressive League, an organi\nzation promoting wider understanding\nof current public issues, in conjunc\ntion with leaders of various Nebraska\nand Omaha organizations.\nThe CIO meeting addressed by\nErickson, a conference of CIO state\nindustrial union council officers, reg\nional directors, international repre\nsentatives and PAC leaders, mapped\nplans for CIO participation in the\nmass petition drive and other pro\ngrams of the Regional Committee for\nMVA. The AFL meeting was a Ne\nbraska Federation of Labor Conven\ntion, with J. J, Guenther, federation\npresident and vice president of the\nNebraska MVA Committee, presiding.\nThe Luverne, Minn., meeting Thurs\nday was the first large public meet\ning on MVA in Minnesota. It was\nattended largely by members of REA\nco-operatives in the southwestern\ncorner of the state, the only portion\nof Minnesota lying directly within the\nMissouri river drainage basin. The\nfilms \"TVA\" and \"The River\" were\nshown at the meeting, which was or\nganized by Leroy C. Sabie of Pipe\nstone, Minnesota representative on\nthe Regional Committee for MVA ex\necutive committee.\nFurther evidence of Minnesota\nawakening to the urgency of the MVA\nissue was reflected in the action of\ntwo labor groups meeting August 28.\nBoth thg CIO state executive board,\nin session in Minneapolis, and the\nMinneapolis Building Trades Council\n(AFL) endorsed MVA. Minneapolis\nMayor Hubert H. Humphrey is a\nmember of the executive committee\nof the regional organization.\nIn Topeka, Kansas, September 5,\n175 persons attending a statewide edu\ncational conference on MVA voted un\nanimously to organize a Kansas Com\nmittee for MVA. The group adopted\na resolution supporting the Murray\nCoehran MVA bills and sharply at\ntacking the Army Engineers and Rec\nlamation Bureau, agencies seeking to\nPage Three)\n<c.\nitinued\nTRADE UNIONS\nAND CO-OPS HOLD\nINSTITUTE\nTrade Union Members\nStudy at Co-op and Labor\nInstitute; Call for\nDevelopment of Economic\nAction Committees.\nMADISON, Wise. (CLNS)\u2014Eighteen\nleaders from trade unions took part\nIn a two weeks period of training\nhere this summer for more direct par\nticipation in union and coo-perative\naction.\nThis special institute was\nconducted by Rochdale Institute, na\ntional co-operative training school as\npart of the School for Workers of the\nUniversity of Wisconsin,\nwere sent by trade unions and co-op\neratives to receive training that would\nenable them to go back to their or\nganizations and work within the labor\ncommunity to build consumer co-op\nStudents\nKeynote for action was sounded in\na special panel before all members\nof the School for Workers when labor\nleaders, two AFL an dtwo CIO, called\nfor labor participation in changing the\neconomic structure of the nation. De\nclaring that \"collective bargaining can\nonly do half the job in securing better\nliving conditions for workers,\" Wil\nliam E. Brennan. AFL labor leader of\nSt. Paul for over 40 years, called for\nthe organization of Economic Action\nCommittees in every union,\ncommittees would awake union mem\nbers to the necessity of making basic\nchanges in the present system of\nmonopoly ownership and urge forma\ntion of consumer co-operatives to aid\nin the task.\n\"Only in this way\", stated Mr. Bren\nnan \"can the objective of providing\nworkers with a higher standard of\nliving be reached. Unions need not\nfear that their energies will be drained\noff through consumer action. Their\nprogram cannot be complete with\nout it.\nThese\n(C<\nitinued\nPagre F<\nir)\nSURVEY SHOWS\nWOMEN LACK\nVOTING INTEREST\nNEW YORK.\u2014Believe it or not, the\naverage working girl isn't much in\nterested in voting.\nThat's the conclusion of Columbia\nUniversity Professors Paul I-azarsfeld\nand Bernard Bereisen, who wrote In\na recent issue of the Public Opinion\nQuarterly that the women's vote con\nstitutes a major problem for the CIO\nPolitical Action Committee as it girds\nfor the municipal campaigns of 1945\nand the 1946 congressional elections.\nThe Lazarsfeld-Berelson study, con\nducted during the last campaign\namong 2,000 women in key industrial\ncenters as New York, Chicago, Cleve\nland and Kansas City, produced the\ndisturbing fact that while only 10%\nof the women in professional or semi\nprofessional positions or the wives of\nmen in these fields failed to vote,\n23% of wage-earning women or the\nwives of wage-earning men did not\nvisit the polls.\nWhile the 1944 presidential\npa\u00eegn evinced greater participation by\nwomen than in 1936 and 1940, the edu\ncator's poll disclosed the unavoidable\nfaet that greater stimulation is needed\namong the employed of the fairer sex,\nCTO-PAC officials stated this week.\nThe study further indicated that the\nfailure of the working woman to vote\nwas not just accidental but was deep\nseated and revealed a \"long-run anti\nsuffrage prejudice. Clearly, the high\nest per centage of non voters is to\nbe found among the low income\nhousewives\u2014many of them the wives\nof union members, many of them the\nwives of men who followed PAC lead\nership in 1944.\"\npoll takers, if PAC's drive to bring\nmore women to the polls, is success\nful \"it would have tapped the major\nreservoir of political power in the\nUnited States.\"\nI am\nAccording to the\nCHAIRMAN OF REGIONAL\nMVA COMMITTEE TELLS\nNEED FOR DEVELOPMENT\nCites Fact That the Missouri Valley Is An\nEconomically-Backward and Economically\nDeclining Region; Calls Attention To\nEffect of This Condition On Other Sections\nOf the Country.\nBy LEIF ERICKSON, Chairman, Regional Committee for MVA\nSparked by organized labor, the Missouri Valley Regional\nCommittee is now conducting a mass petition drive aimed at\nproviding evidence of broad, popular support for the Missouri\nValley Authority legislation pending in congress.\nThe committee expects to reach every trade unionist and\nsmall farmer in a combination informational and petition drive.\n-\u2666Through\nHEARINGS ON\nMURRAY MVA BILL\nSTART SEPT. 18\nLeading officials\nof the Regional Committee for MVA\nwill testify in support of the Missouri\nValley Authority bill, S. 556, at hear\nings opening September 18 before a\nsenate Irrigation sub-committee.\nWASHINGTON.\nLeif Erickson of Helena, Mont.,\nchairman, Raymond R. Tucker of St.\nLouis, Mo., vice chairman, and John\nE. Wetzlg of Kansas City, Mo., treas\nurer, are scheduled to testify some\ntime during the five days in which\nproponents of the measure will pre\nsent their case. Others who will urge\npassage of the measure include Sen.\nJames E. Murray, sponsor of the bill;\nMorris L. Cooke, former REA admin\nistrator; Rt. Rev. Msgr. John O'Grady,\nsecretary of the National Conference\nof Catholic Charities: Fred V. Heinkel,\npresident of the Missouri Farmers\nAssociation; Missouri State\nClaude B. Ricketts, chairman of the\nMissouri MVA Commission;\nspokesmen for the National Farmers\nUnion, CIO and AFL. D. W, Chap\nman, state president of the Farmers\nUnion will testify before the commit\nSen.\nand\ntee.\nFollowing the week of testimony by\nproponents, the first two days of the\nnext week will be turned over to In\nterior Department representatives and\nthe remainder of the week to oppon\nents of the measure.\nEXECUTIVE SEC.\nPEOPLE'S LOBBY\nHERE SEPT. 25\nBenjamin S. Marsh, executive sec\nretary of the People's Lobby, will\nspeak to an audience in Helena at\nthe Labor Temple on Tuesday eve\nning, September 26. The meeting is\nopen and everyone is invited to at\ntend.\nMr. Marsh has his headquarters in\nthe national capital, has been engaged\nin legislative work for nearly forty\nyears, eleven years at Albany, N. Y.\nand over twenty-seven at Washington.\nDr. Francis J. McConnell, bishop of\nthe Methodist church In the New York\narea, until his recent retirement, is\npresident of the Lobby.\nThe Lobby which has members in 37\nstates is working for a national legis\nlative program in congress. Including\ntaxation of land values, incomes\u2014per\nsonal and corporate, and of estates,\nand repeal of consumption taxes; and\npublic ownership or social controls,\nof natural resources, natural monop\nolies and basic industries.\nMr. Marsh has studied conditions In\nEurope, and in 1939 made his eighth\ntrip to Europe since 1929.\nHe is a graduate of Grlnnell college,\nIowa, where he was elected to Phi\nBeta Kappa, and did five years grad\nuate work in history, economics and\npolitics in Chicago and Pennsylvania\nuniversities.\nHe was secretary of the Pennsyl\nvania Society for the Prevention of\nCruelty to Children in Philadelphia,\nof the New York City Congestion\nCommittee and Municipal Ownership\nLeague, and was appointed by then\nGovernor Hughes, secretary of the N.\nY. State Commission on Distribution\nof Population.\nIn Washington, he was director of\nthe Farmers National Council, of\nprogressive farm organizations, before\n\u25a0d on Pagre Four)\n(Ci\nitii\nERICKSON SPEAKS TO\nLABOR GROUPS\nVigorous activity in support of Mis\nsouri Valley Authority legislation was\nurged by Leif Erickson, chairman of\nthe Regional Committee for MVA, in\na series of talks this week.\nErickson, on his way east for the\nopening of hearings on the Murray\nbill, S. 555, completed a three-day\nspeaking campaign with an address\nbefore a Nebraska statewide confer\nence in Omaha Friday. He addressed\nCIO and AFL groups in Omaha Wed\nnesday and a Southwestern Minnesota\nMVA meeting at Luverne, Minn.,\nThursday. He is presiding at a meet\ning of the Regional Committee for\nMVA executive committee in Omaha\nSaturday.\nestablished organiza\ntions, such as the CIO, Building\nand Construction Trades Coun\ncils and other AFL groups, and\nthe National Farmers Union,\nand through newly-formed citi\nzens committees for MVA in\nthe Missouri valley states, the\nregional committee will see\nthat the MVA message reaches\nvalley.\nThe Regional Committee for MVA\ntogether with leading ecoonmlc and\nagricultural experts, foresee a future\nof scarcity and poverty in our region\nIf congress falls to establish a Mis\nsouri Valley Authority. We do not\nwant that kind of a future. Therefore\nwe are supporting the Murray-Coehran\nbill (S. 555) and call upon every trade\nunionist, whether in or out of the\nMissouri valley, to give this legislation\nhis unqualified backing.\nWe do not say that the Murray\nMVA bill alone will mean full em\nployment and greater economic op\nportunity for the people of this region.\nWe do say, however, that full employ\nment is out of the question without\nthe enactment of such a measure as\nthis providing unified, full develop\nment of the region's natural resources\nand promising the ultimate solution\nof tremendous problems of soil and\nwater. Just as the solution of these\nproblems and the development of the\nland in the Tennessee Valley Author\nity provided jobs for thousands, so can\nthe MVA open the door to increased\nemployment.\nA great storm has been raised over\nan OWI writer's description of an\narea including moat of the Missouri\nvalley states as America's wasteland.\nPerhaps the writer did state his case\ntoo strongly and without a complete\ngrasp of the subject. Still there are\nare any number of facts and statistics\navailable to back up any assertion\nthat the Missouri valley is an econom\nically backward, economically declin\ning region. Due to the great drouths\nand dust storms of the 1930s and the\nlack of irrigation, over 350,000 people\nmigrated from the upper valley from\n1930 to 1940,\npersonal income declined 12%, salaries\n20%, and manufacturing 30%. Such\ndepressing economic facts, if un\nchanged, spell out one w r ord for the\nfuture\u2014depression.\nThe Regional Committee for MVA\nwants to see the end of these condi\ntions. It looks to a future when the\ngeneration and distribution of low-cost\npower and the tapping of hte region's\nrich mineral resources, with corre\nsponding stimulation of industry and\nagriculture, will make of this river\nvalley a young valley, chock full of\nnew-found strength.\nThis was the plan of the late Presi\ndent Roosevelt when he proposed to\ncongress the establishment of such\nauthorities in seven strategic locations\nthroughout the nation. We can see,\ntoo, the great wisdom of this proposal\nwhen we realize that poverty in one\nsection of the country has its effect\nIn that same period,\non other sections of the country.\nIn its attitude toward MVA, as in its\nposition on all other vital Issues, or\nganized labor must be concerned with\nthe welfare of all the people of the\ncountry. While MVA means more jobs\nand a stronger labor movement, in\nsupporting the Murray-Coehran legis\nlation. labor will be supporting, too,\nthe Missouri valley farmer whose\ncrops are destroyed by recurrent\nfloods or drouth and who has not\nhad the benefit of nearby markets\nor of rural electrification and use of\nthe electrical appliances that are nec\nessities in any home. In supporting\nMVA, labor will be aiding too the\nMissouri valley small businessman\nwhose business has failed to expand\nthrough lacq of low-rate power and\nlow-rate transportation,\nsupporting this legislation, also will\nhave in mind the ex-servicemen\u2014\nmany of them union members\u2014who\nwill be expecting and deserving jobs\nand those other. ex-servicemen who\nlook for the irrigation of arid lands\nand federal encouragement of family\ntype farming, when they return from\nthe wars. All of this is akin to la\nbor's hopes for a prosperous and se\ncure future, for we know that pros\nperity, like peace is indivisible. We\nall must have it or none of us can\nhave it.\nLabor, in\nWith reference to charges of op\nposition to MVA by private power in\nterests in Montana and elsewhere, the\ncommittee has called on Attorney Gen\neral Tom Clark for an early and com\nplete investigation of \"wide-spread\nrumors that the power holding com\nContinued on Pagre Four)","height":"21219","width":"16266"}}
